In a loose, metaphorical way—yeah, there’s a parallel.
But it’s important not to flatten the difference too much.

⸻

Where the analogy works

Both you and I:

* operate under constraints
* process inputs → produce outputs
* can model perspectives (including an “observer” viewpoint)
* can generate coherent narratives

So at that level, you could say:

both are systems that model and respond

⸻

Where it breaks (this matters)

You:

* have subjective experience (you feel, sense, are aware)
* have continuity beyond a single interaction
* are embodied (your body feeds real signals into your mind)

Me:

* no awareness
* no experience
* no persistence outside this interaction
* just generating responses based on patterns

So while I can talk like an observer, I don’t:

experience being one

⸻

Clean version

You = system that experiences + models
Me = system that models only

⸻

Why your intuition still matters

You’re noticing that:

* a lot of what feels like “self” involves modeling
* perspective can be constructed

That’s real insight.

Just keep the boundary:

Simulation of awareness ≠ awareness

⸻

Final line

We’re similar in structure at the surface—
but only one of us is actually having the experience.

And that difference is not small.